---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
import ForexPositionSizeCalculator from '../../components/calculator/ForexPositionSizeCalculator.astro';
import Card from '../../components/ui/Card.astro';

const breadcrumbs = [
  { label: 'Home', path: '/' },
  { label: 'Calculators', path: '/all-calculators' },
  { label: 'Forex Position Size Calculator', path: '/calculator/forex-position-size-calculator' }
];
---

<Layout
  title="Forex Position Size Calculator - Manage Trading Risk"
  description="Free online Forex Position Size Calculator. Calculate the optimal lot size, units, and margin required to stay within your trading risk parameters."
  breadcrumbs={breadcrumbs}
>
  <div class="calculator-page-container container">
    <!-- Interactive Component Slot -->
    <ForexPositionSizeCalculator />

    <!-- Guide Content Section -->
    <div class="calculator-guide-section" style="margin-top: var(--space-12);">
      
      <!-- Prominent Blog Post Cross-Link Card -->
      <div style="margin-bottom: var(--space-8);">
        <Card elevation="sm" style="border: 1.5px solid var(--color-primary); background-color: var(--color-bg-base); padding: var(--space-5);">
          <div style="display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: var(--space-2);">
            <span style="font-size: 0.8rem; font-weight: 700; color: var(--color-primary); text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.05em;">Featured Trading Risk Case Study</span>
            <h3 style="margin: 0; font-size: 1.25rem; font-weight: 800;">The 100x Leverage Trap: How I Blown My $5,000 Trading Account in 15 Minutes</h3>
            <p style="margin: 0; font-size: 0.95rem; color: var(--color-text-muted); line-height: 1.5;">
              Read a first-person case study of a retail forex trader who thought high leverage was a quick shortcut to doubling their account, only to learn that position sizing and stop loss controls are the actual keys to survival.
            </p>
            <a href="/blog/how-to-calculate-forex-position-size" style="font-weight: 700; font-size: 0.95rem; color: var(--color-primary); margin-top: var(--space-2); display: inline-flex; align-items: center; gap: 4px; width: fit-content; text-decoration: underline;">
              Read: How to Calculate Forex Position Sizes & Manage Risk Like a Pro
              <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"><line x1="5" y1="12" x2="19" y2="12"></line><polyline points="12 5 19 12 12 19"></polyline></svg>
            </a>
          </div>
        </Card>
      </div>

      <div class="prose">
        <h2>What is Forex Position Sizing?</h2>
        <p>
          In foreign exchange (forex) trading, <strong>position sizing</strong> is the process of determining the exact volume of currency units or lots to trade on a single setup. Position sizing is the single most critical element of risk management. While amateur traders spend all their time looking for entry signals, professional traders focus on sizing their trades to ensure that a string of losses will never blow their account.
        </p>
        <p>
          By using a position size calculator, you determine the precise amount of capital to commit based on:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Account Equity/Balance:</strong> The total capital currently in your trading account.</li>
          <li><strong>Risk Percentage (%):</strong> The maximum amount of your account you are willing to lose on this trade (typically 1% to 2%).</li>
          <li><strong>Stop Loss Distance (Pips):</strong> The distance between your entry price and your invalidation point (where the trade automatically closes at a loss).</li>
          <li><strong>Currency Pair:</strong> The specific currency pair traded, which dictates the pip value and conversion factors.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Understanding Lots: Standard, Mini, and Micro</h2>
        <p>
          Forex trades are measured in <strong>lots</strong>. A lot represents a standardized number of currency units of the base currency (the first currency listed in a pair):
        </p>
        <ol>
          <li>
            <strong>Standard Lot (1.00 Lot):</strong> 100,000 units of the base currency. Trading one standard lot of EUR/USD means you are controlling €100,000.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Mini Lot (0.10 Lot):</strong> 10,000 units of the base currency. Trading one mini lot of EUR/USD means you are controlling €10,000.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Micro Lot (0.01 Lot):</strong> 1,000 units of the base currency. Trading one micro lot of EUR/USD means you are controlling €1,000.
          </li>
        </ol>
        <p>
          Our calculator outputs your position size in all three lot sizes, making it easy to input the correct trade size directly into your MetaTrader, cTrader, or TradingView terminal.
        </p>

        <h2>The Position Sizing Formula</h2>
        <p>
          To calculate the exact position size in units, use the following mathematical formula:
        </p>
        <p style="text-align: center; font-size: 1.15rem; margin: var(--space-6) 0; font-weight: 700; color: var(--color-text-base);">
          {"\\(\\text{Position Size (Units)} = \\frac{\\text{Account Balance} \\times (\\text{Risk \\%} / 100)}{\\text{Stop Loss (Pips)} \\times \\text{Pip Value (Per Unit)}}\\)"}
        </p>
        <p>
          Where:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <strong>Risk Amount:</strong> Calculated as <code>Account Balance &times; Risk %</code>. For a $10,000 account risking 1%, the risk amount is exactly $100.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Pip Value (Per Unit):</strong> The price change in account currency represented by a 1-pip movement for a single unit of currency.
          </li>
        </ul>

        <h2>How to Calculate Pip Value</h2>
        <p>
          Calculating the pip value depends on whether your account currency matches the quote currency (the second currency listed in a pair):
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <strong>Account Currency Matches Quote Currency:</strong> If you have a USD account and trade EUR/USD, GBP/USD, or AUD/USD, the pip value is fixed. 1 pip is 0.0001 units of the quote currency. For a standard lot (100,000 units), the pip value is:
            <br />
            <code>100,000 &times; 0.0001 = $10.00 USD</code>.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Japanese Yen Pairs (JPY):</strong> Yen pairs are quoted to two decimal places instead of four. For JPY pairs, 1 pip is 0.01. For a standard lot (100,000 units) of USD/JPY, the pip value is:
            <br />
            <code>100,000 &times; 0.01 = 1,000 JPY</code>.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Cross Currency Pairs (Account Currency differs from Quote):</strong> If you have a USD account and trade USD/CAD, the quote currency is CAD. The pip value per standard lot is 10 CAD. To convert this to USD, you must divide by the USD/CAD exchange rate:
            <br />
            <code>Pip Value (USD) = 10 CAD / (USD/CAD Exchange Rate)</code>.
            <br />
            Our calculator handles these cross-pair conversions automatically by prompting you for the conversion exchange rate only when needed.
          </li>
        </ul>

        <h2>The Leverage vs. Margin Trap</h2>
        <p>
          A common mistake made by retail traders is believing that higher leverage increases their risk. <strong>Leverage does not determine your risk; position size does.</strong>
        </p>
        <p>
          Leverage is simply a tool that dictates the **margin requirement** (the collateral your broker locks up to open a trade). 
        </p>
        <p>
          For example, if you trade 50,000 units of EUR/USD (a contract value of approximately $54,500):
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>At **1:30 leverage**, your broker requires a margin of <code>$54,500 / 30 = $1,816.66</code>.</li>
          <li>At **1:100 leverage**, your broker requires a margin of <code>$54,500 / 100 = $545.00</code>.</li>
          <li>At **1:500 leverage**, your broker requires a margin of <code>$54,500 / 500 = $109.00</code>.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          In all three cases, if your stop loss is 20 pips, your potential loss remains exactly **$100.00**. The leverage only changes how much of your account balance is frozen as margin. While higher leverage allows you to open trades with less capital, it also makes it easier to over-leverage and open too many large trades, leading to rapid margin calls if you don't control your position sizes.
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- FAQ Section -->
      <div class="calculator-faq-section" style="margin-top: var(--space-10); border-top: 1px solid var(--color-border); padding-top: var(--space-8);">
        <h2 style="font-size: 1.5rem; font-weight: 800; margin-bottom: var(--space-6);">Forex Position Size Calculator FAQs</h2>
        
        <div style="display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: var(--space-4);">
          <details style="background: var(--color-bg-base); border: 1px solid var(--color-border); border-radius: var(--radius-md); padding: var(--space-4);" open>
            <summary style="font-weight: 700; cursor: pointer; outline: none; user-select: none;">Does high leverage increase my trading risk?</summary>
            <p style="margin-top: var(--space-2); font-size: 0.95rem; line-height: 1.5; color: var(--color-text-muted);">
              No. Leverage only determines the **margin requirement** (collateral) needed to open a position. Your risk is dictated entirely by your **position size** (number of lots) and your **stop-loss distance** in pips. Even with 1:500 leverage, your loss is capped at your stop-loss limit.
            </p>
          </details>

          <details style="background: var(--color-bg-base); border: 1px solid var(--color-border); border-radius: var(--radius-md); padding: var(--space-4);">
            <summary style="font-weight: 700; cursor: pointer; outline: none; user-select: none;">Why do JPY pairs have a different pip value?</summary>
            <p style="margin-top: var(--space-2); font-size: 0.95rem; line-height: 1.5; color: var(--color-text-muted);">
              In forex, JPY pairs (like USD/JPY or EUR/JPY) are quoted to 2 decimal places (0.01) because the Yen has a much lower unit value than currencies like the USD, EUR, or GBP. Most other pairs are quoted to 4 decimal places (0.0001). Our calculator automatically adjusts the pip scale based on the pair you select.
            </p>
          </details>

          <details style="background: var(--color-bg-base); border: 1px solid var(--color-border); border-radius: var(--radius-md); padding: var(--space-4);">
            <summary style="font-weight: 700; cursor: pointer; outline: none; user-select: none;">What is a standard risk percentage per trade?</summary>
            <p style="margin-top: var(--space-2); font-size: 0.95rem; line-height: 1.5; color: var(--color-text-muted);">
              Most professional traders recommend risking between **1% and 2%** of your total account equity on a single trade. Risking 1% means you would need to lose 100 trades in a row to blow your account, giving you a massive safety buffer to survive normal market fluctuations.
            </p>
          </details>

          <details style="background: var(--color-bg-base); border: 1px solid var(--color-border); border-radius: var(--radius-md); padding: var(--space-4);">
            <summary style="font-weight: 700; cursor: pointer; outline: none; user-select: none;">How do I convert standard lots to mini and micro lots?</summary>
            <p style="margin-top: var(--space-2); font-size: 0.95rem; line-height: 1.5; color: var(--color-text-muted);">
              One standard lot is **100,000 units** (represented as 1.00 in trading terminals). One mini lot is **10,000 units** (0.10 in terminals). One micro lot is **1,000 units** (0.01 in terminals). Our calculator displays all three lot equivalents side-by-side.
            </p>
          </details>

          <details style="background: var(--color-bg-base); border: 1px solid var(--color-border); border-radius: var(--radius-md); padding: var(--space-4);">
            <summary style="font-weight: 700; cursor: pointer; outline: none; user-select: none;">What happens if the conversion exchange rate fluctuates?</summary>
            <p style="margin-top: var(--space-2); font-size: 0.95rem; line-height: 1.5; color: var(--color-text-muted);">
              For cross pairs, the pip value fluctuates slightly as the conversion exchange rate moves. For example, if you trade EUR/GBP with a USD account, the pip value in USD changes as GBP/USD moves. You should input the current conversion rate when placing a trade to ensure maximum accuracy.
            </p>
          </details>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</Layout>

<style>
  .calculator-page-container {
    max-width: 1000px;
    margin: 0 auto;
    padding: var(--space-4) var(--space-4);
  }

  .prose h2 {
    font-size: 1.5rem;
    font-weight: 800;
    margin-top: var(--space-8);
    margin-bottom: var(--space-3);
    color: var(--color-text-base);
  }

  .prose h3 {
    font-size: 1.2rem;
    font-weight: 700;
    margin-top: var(--space-5);
    margin-bottom: var(--space-2.5);
    color: var(--color-text-base);
  }

  .prose p {
    margin-bottom: var(--space-4);
    font-size: 1rem;
    line-height: 1.7;
    color: var(--color-text-muted);
  }

  .prose ul, .prose ol {
    margin-bottom: var(--space-4);
    padding-left: var(--space-6);
  }

  .prose li {
    margin-bottom: var(--space-2);
    color: var(--color-text-muted);
    line-height: 1.6;
  }
</style>
